This project is about Fourier decoupling inequalities, related oscillatory integrals and applications. The project outcomes include:





1.The PI and collaborators obtained optimal Fourier decoupling inequalities for all quadratic forms; the paper was published at Duke Math. Journal in 2023;





2.The PI and collaborators studied Hormander-type oscillatory integrals; in particular, they proposed a new curvature condition, called Bourgains condition, which unified the study of the classical Fourier restriction problem, the Bochner-Riesz problem, the local smoothing estimates for linear Schrodinger equations, etc. The paper was published at Inventiones Math. in 2024;





3.The PI and collaborators applied tools from logic to the study of oscillatory integrals, and obtained the sharp convergence exponents of Tarrys problem in dimension two; the paper was published at J. Eur. Math. Soc. in 2024;





4.The PI and collaborators applied Fourier decoupling inequalities to geometric measure theory, and solved a conjecture of Fassler and Orponen (2014); they finished two papers: One was published at Cambridge J. Math. in 2024, and the other was accepted at American J. Math.











The PI organized two summer schools at the University of Wisconsin-Madison, in 2022 and 2023 separately. These two summer schools attracted about 30 and 25, separately, graduate students and postdocs from the US and Europe. In each summer school, the PI organized two panel discussions, and invited senior colleagues to share their experience in job hunting (writing research statements and teaching statements, asking for reference letters), developing a personal research agenda and other early career issues.








